Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button on `EditProductPage`

In your page XAML, use `BackButtonBehavior` to replace the default back arrow:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2. ViewModel with Cancel Command

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    public IRelayCommand CancelCommand { get; }

    public EditProductViewModel()
    {
        CancelCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnCancelAsync);
    }

    async Task OnCancelAsync()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "Discard your changes?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return; // user chose to stay
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

## 3. Guard the Hardware/Gesture Back Too

The `CancelCommand` handles your button, but the user can also swipe back or press the Android hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back-navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard your changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because the confirmation dialog is async — without it, navigation completes before the user answers.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- `deferral.Complete()` must always be called (discard *or* stay) to release the deferral.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the visible "Cancel" button; `OnNavigating` catches swipe-back and hardware-back.
